"text":" ","children":[{"tag":"inline","attrib":{},"text":"Abolition of Court","children":[],"tail":".—"}],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":"The Temporary Emergency Court of Appeals created by section 211(b) of the Economic Stabilization Act of 1970 [","children":[{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/91/379"},"text":"Pub. L. 91–379","children":[],"tail":", formerly set out as a note under "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/usc/t12/s1904"},"text":"section 1904 of Title 12","children":[],"tail":", Banks and Banking] is abolished, effective 6 months after the date of the enactment of this Act ["},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1992-10-29"},"text":"Oct. 29, 1992","children":[],"tail":"]."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"subsection","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"e"},"text":"“(e)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":" ","children":[{"tag":"inline","attrib":{},"text":"Pending Cases","children":[],"tail":".—"}],"tail":null},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"1"},"text":"(1)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" Any appeal which, before the effective date of abolition described in subsection (d), is pending in the Temporary Emergency Court of Appeals but has not been submitted to a panel of such court as of that date shall be assigned to the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit as though the appeal had originally been filed in that court.","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"paragraph","attrib":{},"text":null,"children":[{"tag":"num","attrib":{"value":"2"},"text":"“(2)","children":[],"tail":null},{"tag":"content","attrib":{},"text":" Any case which, before the effective date of abolition described in subsection (d), has been submitted to a panel of the Temporary Emergency Court of Appeals and as to which the mandate has not been issued as of that date shall remain with that panel for all purposes and, notwithstanding the provisions of sections 291 and 292 of title 28, United States Code, that panel shall be assigned to the United States Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit for the purpose of deciding such case.”","children":[],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"note","attrib":{"topic":"miscellaneous","id":"id529d893b-3a70-11f1-9e0c-dcbb1364dae6"},"text":"\n","children":[{"tag":"heading","attrib":{},"text":"Termination of United States District Court for the District of the Canal Zone","children":[],"tail":"\n"},{"tag":"p","attrib":{},"text":"For termination of the United States District Court for the District of the Canal Zone at end of the “transition period”, being the 30-month period beginning ","children":[{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1979-10-01"},"text":"Oct. 1, 1979","children":[],"tail":", and ending midnight "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1982-03-31"},"text":"Mar. 31, 1982","children":[],"tail":", see Paragraph 5 of Article XI of the Panama Canal Treaty of 1977 and sections 2101 and 2201 to 2203 of "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/pl/96/70/tII"},"text":"Pub. L. 96–70, title II","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"date","attrib":{"date":"1979-09-27"},"text":"Sept. 27, 1979","children":[],"tail":", "},{"tag":"ref","attrib":{"href":"/us/stat/93/493"},"text":"93 Stat. 493","children":[],"tail":", formerly classified to sections 3831 and 3841 to 3843, respectively, of Title 22, Foreign Relations and Intercourse."}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":"\n"}],"tail":null}
